- I dislike overly intimate/piano‑centric mic‑forward mixes, sparse percussion that robs groove, heavy multiband/bus compression or pushed mastering that flattens dynamics, narrow center‑front imaging, muddied low end and synth/string‑first pop gloss or ear‑fatiguing radio processing.
Evaluation and reasoned choice
- Authentic 1976 AOR mix matches my preferences almost exactly. Its description emphasizes guitar‑driven, big layered overdriven electrics (direct match to my AOR/guitar‑forward preference), roomy natural reverb, tactile midrange and wide stereo imaging (all items I look for in the mid/top imaging and ambience). It explicitly calls out punchy propulsive low end and tight rhythmic pockets and expressive electric solos — those are central to my desire for groove and tasteful, tactile electric work. It also notes multi‑tracked natural harmonies and a restrained remaster that preserves headroom, which aligns with my wish for tight harmonies, upfront midrange vocals and preserved dynamics/micro‑dynamics. In short, the AOR mix is a one‑to‑one fit with the attributes I prioritized.
- Collector‑grade ELO anthology also ticks many positive boxes: warm analog remasters with tape sheen, midrange punch, propulsive low end, wide stereo imaging, natural‑room tight harmony vocals and tasteful electric solos, plus a cohesive single‑disc sequencing and restrained mastering that preserves headroom. Those features address several of my likes (tape warmth, harmony vocals, midrange clarity). However, two specific issues make it the less optimal pick for me:
  1. The ELO anthology description includes “slightly pushed analog remasters.” Even if still largely restrained, “slightly pushed” raises a warning relative to my explicit dislike of pushed mastering / heavy compression that flattens dynamics. I prioritize preserved headroom and micro‑dynamics, and any hint of pushed remastering reduces fidelity to that preference.
  2. ELO’s historic production aesthetic often foregrounds orchestral/string and synth textures alongside pop arrangements. My self‑stated dislike of synth/string‑first pop gloss means that, despite good midrange punch and harmony vocals, the anthology’s orchestral/pop sheen is a potential conflict with my taste for guitar‑forward AOR intimacy and clear, overdriven guitar textures. By contrast, the Authentic 1976 AOR mix explicitly centers layered overdriven guitars and tight rhythmic pockets rather than orchestral/synth elements.
Conclusion
Given the near‑perfect alignment of the Authentic 1976 AOR mix with my detailed list of sonic preferences (guitar focus, roomy reverb, tactile midrange, punchy low end, expressive solos, multi‑part harmonies and restrained remastering) and the potential mismatches in the ELO anthology (slightly pushed remastering and likely orchestral/synth pop emphasis), I select the Authentic 1976 AOR mix as the CD that best fits my stated preferences and avoids the qualities I dislike.

